A debounce function limits the rate at which a function can fire, executing it only after a specified delay since the last call:
```js
function debounce(func, wait) {
  let timeout;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), wait);
  };
}

// Example usage
const handleResize = debounce(() => {
  console.log('Window resized');
}, 300);

window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);
```

In this example, the `handleResize` function will only be called once every 300ms at most, even if the window is resized multiple times in quick succession. This is useful for optimizing performance when dealing with events that fire frequently.

The `debounce` function works by returning a new function that wraps the original one. Whenever this new function is called, it clears any existing timeout and sets a new one. If the function is called again before the timeout expires, the timeout is reset. Only once the delay (`wait`) has passed without any new calls will the original function be executed.

The `...args` syntax is used to pass along any arguments to the original function, and `func.apply(this, args)` ensures that the original function's `this` context is preserved.
